body:
I recently find out an index property could be `PropertyChanged` trigger using the `Item[]` property name.

The const could be found in the `System.Windows.Data.Binding.IndexerName`.
```C#
//
// Summary:
//     Used as the System.ComponentModel.PropertyChangedEventArgs.PropertyName of System.ComponentModel.PropertyChangedEventArgs
//     to indicate that an indexer property has changed.
public const string IndexerName = "Item[]";
```

At the moment the `Fody/PropertyChanged` show a warning and ignore the indexer property.
```
Property is an indexer. Property will be ignored. You can suppress this warning with [SuppressPropertyChangedWarnings].
```

Would be handy if `Fody/PropertyChanged` consider an indexer property as `Item[]` instead of ignoring.

This would enable to use `[AlsoNotifyFor(Binding.IndexerName)]` or `[DependsOn(Binding.IndexerName)]`.

I could open a PR, just need some time to find out how `Fody/PropertyChanged` works.

﻿using System;
using System.ComponentModel;

namespace PropertyChanged;

/// <summary>
/// Specifies that the class will be marked with <see cref="INotifyPropertyChanged"/>.
/// Note that all classes that implement <see cref="INotifyPropertyChanged"/> will have property notification
/// injected irrespective of the use of this attribute.
/// Raising an issue about "this attribute does not behave as expected" will result in a RTFM and the issue being closed.
/// </summary>
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Struct | AttributeTargets.Record, Inherited = true)]
public class AddINotifyPropertyChangedInterfaceAttribute : Attribute;

#### Describe the issue

When creating a classlibrary with **.NET-Standard 2.0** there is a compilation-error with weaving the OnPropertyChanged Event into a class that has not implemented the Event. 

The Compilation Error then says: 
"_Feature 'nullable reference types' is not available in C# 7.3. Please use language version 8.0 or greater._"

#### Minimal Repro

- Create a new .NET-Standard 2.0 Classlibrary-Project with Visual Studio 2022 Community (latest on 04.04.2024). 
 - Install The "PropertyChanged.Fody"-NuGet, the "Fody"-NuGet will automatically be installed as an transitive package. (Installing the "Fody" package manually does not change the behavior of this problem)
- Create a public partial Class with at least one public Property.
- Add a reference ``using PropertyChanged;``
- Firstly build the library to ensure, that the file "FodyWeavers.xml" is beeing created. Also ensure, that the Tag ``<PropertyChanged />`` is placed inside the ``<Weavers></Weavers>`` Tags
- Add an attribute in the line before the class declaration: ``[AddINotifyPropertyChangedInterface]``

Example:
```csharp
    [AddINotifyPropertyChangedInterface]
    public partial class Class1
    {
        public string Name { get; set; }
    }
```

If you look at the file the error refers to (PropertyChanged.g.cs), you can see the problem in the output file, where a nullable string is beeing created as parameter of the OnPropertyChanged method:
```csharp
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;
    protected void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string? propertyName = null)
    {
        OnPropertyChanged(new PropertyChangedEventArgs(propertyName));
    }
    protected virtual void OnPropertyChanged(PropertyChangedEventArgs eventArgs)
    {
        PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, eventArgs);
    }
```

#### You should already be a Patron

I'm not a Patron, sorry, still new to the library and checking it out

#### Describe the issue

Weavers don't run for a simple project.

#### Minimal Repro

.NET 6 [WpfApp1.zip](https://github.com/Fody/PropertyChanged/files/14628969/WpfApp1.zip)
.NET 7 [WpfApp3.zip](https://github.com/Fody/PropertyChanged/files/14629095/WpfApp3.zip)


1. Create a blank WPF Project
2. Add Fody and PropertyChanged.Fody (Also, obviously add FodyWeavers.xml)
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<Weavers xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="FodyWeavers.xsd">
  <PropertyChanged />
</Weavers>
```
4. Create a class that implements `INotifyPropertyChanged`
5. Create a property such as `public int Hello { get; set; }`

e.g.
```cs
namespace WpfApp1
{
    partial class FileName : INotifyPropertyChanged
    {
        public int Hello { get; set; }
    }
}
```

6. Add the class to MainWindow. E.g.

```cs
    public partial class MainWindow : Window
    {
        FileName FileName;
        public MainWindow()
        {
            InitializeComponent();
        }
    }
```

7. Build

The code generator works (as we can see)
```cs
namespace WpfApp1
{
    partial class FileName
    {
        [GeneratedCode("PropertyChanged.Fody", "4.1.0.0")]
        public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;

        [GeneratedCode("PropertyChanged.Fody", "4.1.0.0"), DebuggerNonUserCode]
        protected void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string? propertyName = null)
        {
            OnPropertyChanged(new PropertyChangedEventArgs(propertyName));
        }

        [GeneratedCode("PropertyChanged.Fody", "4.1.0.0"), DebuggerNonUserCode]
        protected virtual void OnPropertyChanged(PropertyChangedEventArgs eventArgs)
        {
            PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, eventArgs);
        }
    }
}
```
But weaver does not seem to run. FileName.Hello setter and getter are blank, and there is no OnPropertyNameChanged (`OnHelloChanged`) being created.

#### Make an effort to fix the bug

I've been researching this for hours but cannot find what would cause this.

Good morning,

Just a quick question, which I hope is OK. What is the best way to perform a validation on a value being set? 

Let's say I had this in my code before using Fody/PropertyChanged:
```
private int quantity;
public bool CannotBeMoreThanOne = true;

public int Quantity
{
    get
    {
        return quantity;
    }
    set
    {
        if (CannotBeMoreThanOne)
            value = Math.Max(1, value);

        quantity = value;
        RaisePropertyChanged();
    }
}
```

With PropertyChanged, my code became this:
```
public bool CannotBeMoreThanOne = true;

public int Quantity { get; set; }
```
And I ended up losing the validation. I thought of doing this but I'm afraid I think I'm sending my code in an endless recursive loop:
```
public void OnQuantityChanged()
{
  if (CannotBeMoreThanOne)
  Quantity = Math.Max(1, Quantity);
}
```

Hopefully someone can point me right direction to validate my models using PropertyChanged. Thanks! ^^

